 and twenty-first centuries. This book brings to light the richness and diversity of Connecticut’s indigenous histories, corrects misinformation about the vanishing Connecticut Indian, and reveals the significant roles and contributions of Native Americans to modern-day Connecticut.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aIndians of North AmericazConnecticutxAntiquities. 0aIndians of North AmericazConnecticutxFolklore. 0aIndians of North AmericazConnecticutxHistory. 0aOral traditionzConnecticut. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aDavison, Faith Damon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant-Costa, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant-Costa, Paul.1 aLavin, Lucianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVolpe, Rosemary, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030019519440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300195194423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300195194/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles